üö® CRITICAL: Assembly has NO overflow protection!

Real incident: Cetus DEX - $223M loss (May 2025)
Cause: Assembly arithmetic overflow

‚ùå VULNERABLE (Cetus-style vulnerability):
assembly {
let result := add(a, b)  // NO OVERFLOW CHECK!
let product := mul(x, y) // NO OVERFLOW CHECK!
mstore(0x00, result)
}

‚úÖ SOLUTION 1 - Add manual checks:
assembly {
let result := add(a, b)
// Manual overflow check
if lt(result, a) {
revert(0, 0)  // Overflow detected
}
}

‚úÖ SOLUTION 2 - Use Solidity instead:
// Let Solidity handle overflow checks
uint256 result = a + b;  // Automatic overflow check

‚úÖ SOLUTION 3 - SafeMath for assembly:
function safeAdd(uint256 a, uint256 b) internal pure returns (uint256) {
uint256 c;
assembly {
c := add(a, b)
}
require(c >= a, "Overflow");  // Check outside assembly
return c;
}

Assembly arithmetic operations with NO checks:
- add(a, b)     ‚Üí wraps on overflow
- sub(a, b)     ‚Üí wraps on underflow
- mul(a, b)     ‚Üí wraps on overflow
- div(a, b)     ‚Üí returns 0 if b is 0 (no revert!)

‚ö†Ô∏è Only use assembly arithmetic when absolutely necessary
and with manual overflow checks!
